6. Fix the hideLoadingScreen() method

```javascript
hideLoadingScreen() {
    try {
        const loading = document.getElementById('loading');
        if (loading) {
            loading.style.opacity = '0';
            setTimeout(() => {
                if (loading && loading.parentNode) {
                    loading.style.display = 'none';
                }
            }, 300);
        }
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('Error hiding loading screen:', error);
        // Force hide after timeout
        setTimeout(() => {
            const loading = document.getElementById('loading');
            if (loading) loading.style.display = 'none';
        }, 1000);
    }
}
```

Summary of Required Changes:

1. Remove the nested DOMContentLoaded - the outer event listener is already handling DOM readiness
2. Add null checks for all getElementById calls in event listeners
3. Use setTimeout in the ready-state check for better reliability
4. Add fallback for loading screen if it fails to hide
5. Ensure all container elements exist before trying to render into them

These changes ensure that the app waits for DOM elements to be available before trying to access them, preventing the "loading but doesn't open" issue. The key is that document.readyState === 'loading' needs to be checked at the right time, and all DOM accesses need proper null checking.
